Teaching Rating Dataset

This is a dataaset on course evaluations, course characteristics, and professor characteristics for 463 courses for the academic years 20002002 at the University of Texas at Austin.

data(data = "TeachingRatings", package = "AER")

tr1 <- TeachingRatings %>%
  mutate( female = if_else(gender == "female",1,0), 
          male = if_else(gender == "male",1,0) ) %>%
  mutate_at(.vars = c("gender", "minority", "tenure", "female", "male"), .funs = function(x){as.factor(x)})
tr1 %>%
  dplyr::select(eval, tenure, gender) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%

\[ eval = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}beauty + \delta gender + e\]

We can interpret the coefficients as follows:

\(\beta_0\): the intercept, or the predicted outcome when X=0 and W=0.

\(\beta_1\): the slope (or main effect) of beauty; for a one unit change in X, the predicted change in Y.

\(\delta\): the slope (or main effect) of gender; for a one unit change in W the predicted change in Y.

Dummies are best thought of as shifts in the constant. Thus, the new intercept for the female line is the coefficient on catcher plus the original intercept.

\[ E(eval) = \begin{cases} (\beta_{0} + \delta) + \beta_1 beauty., & \text{female}=1 \\ \beta_{0} +\beta_1 beauty., & \text{female} = 0 \end{cases} \]

What about substantive effects. What is our predicted eval for the mean female and the mean male from our dummy variable regression?

                  color = gender), data = lines.df)

Notice the different intercepts we predicted, but the slopes are the same.

Multiple categorical variables

Create age group

Here, we create an age_group categorical variable. If a professor is in 30-39, then we code age_group as 1; If 40-49, we code age_group as 2, If 50-59, we code age_group as 3; If 60 and above, then 4

tr1 <- tr1 %>%
  mutate(age_group  = if_else(age <40 ,1 ,
                      if_else(age <50 ,2,
                      if_else(age <60 ,3, 4))) %>% as.factor())
ggplot(tr1, aes(x = age_group, fill = age_group )) +
  geom_bar()

m_cat <- lm(eval ~ age_group + beauty, tr1) 
coef(m_cat)
## (Intercept)  age_group2  age_group3  age_group4      beauty 
## 3.945220309 0.075307935 0.094569497 0.007652922 0.137096194

Visualization

# Calculate race-specific intercepts
intercepts <- c(coef(m_cat)["(Intercept)"],
                coef(m_cat)["(Intercept)"] + coef(m_cat)["age_group2"],
                coef(m_cat)["(Intercept)"] + coef(m_cat)["age_group2"] +
coef(m_cat)["age_group3"],
 coef(m_cat)["(Intercept)"] + coef(m_cat)["age_group2"] +
coef(m_cat)["age_group3"] +coef(m_cat)["age_group4"] )
                
lines.df <- data.frame(intercepts = intercepts,
                       slopes = rep(coef(m_cat)["beauty"], 4),
                       age_group = levels(tr1$age_group))              

qplot(x = beauty, y = eval, color = age_group, data = tr1) + 
  geom_abline(aes(intercept = intercepts, 
                  slope = slopes, color = age_group), data = lines.df)

Interaction Analysis

Marginal Effect

Marginal effects tells us how a dependent variable (outcome) changes when a specific independent variable (explanatory variable) changes. Other covariates are assumed to be held constant. Marginal effects are often calculated when analyzing regression analysis results.

For example, we have this model:

\[ \hat eval_i = \hat \beta_0 +\hat \beta_1 beauty_i + \hat \beta_2 age + u \]

The marginal effect of beauty and age on eval?

$$ = _1; = _2

$$

Interpretation: One unit increase in beauty is associated with \(\hat{\beta}_1\) XX unit change change in eval, holding all equal.

Interacting dummy variable with dummy variable

\[\hat{eval_i} = \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 female_i + \hat{\beta}_2 tenure_i + \hat{\beta}_3 female_i*tenure_i + u \]

# two equaviliant way of interaction
m_inter1 <- lm(eval ~ gender*tenure ,  tr1)

m_inter2 <- lm(eval ~  gender + tenure + gender:tenure ,  tr1) 
stargazer(m_inter1,m_inter2, header = F, type = "text")
